titre: Och Was Ik Maar Bij Moeder Thuis Gebleven
Och Was Ik Maar Bij Moeder Thuis Gebleven
We Gaan Er Met Z'n Allen Onderdoor
Giant's Mermaid, The - Des Riesen Nixe
You Make Me Feel Like A Natural Woman
Kun Je Nog Zingen, Zing Dan Mee! 3e Serie

description: With supersize spiral bound A3 score.  In the middle of the 19th century, European ballet was associated largely with stories of tragedy and gloom. In contrast, the ballet Coppélia, premiered in 1870 with music by Léo Delibes and choreography by Arthur Saint-Léon, tells the happily-ever-after story of the toymaker Dr. Coppélius, his life-sized doll, and two young lovers.

Another fabulous arrangement from Adrian Taylor of popular tunes for Junior Wind Ensemble.  It is not necessary to have all parts being played for these arrangements. Most will work fine with just the two Trumpet/Clarinet parts and a bass line from trombones, tubas or bassoons. With the exception of the bassoon part, all instruments have a part 1 (more advanced and with key signatures) and a part 2 (easier music,
titre: Music for Junior Wind Band Vol. 3

description: The long awaited Music for Junior Wind Band. A flexible book of popular tunes for beginner wind band.
titre: Music for Junior Wind Band Vol. 2

description: The long awaited Music for Junior Wind Band. A flexible book of popular tunes for beginner wind band.
titre: Music for Junior Wind Band Vol. 1

description: Blues for Big Ears is one of Mark Nightingales’ Easy Jazzy Tudes, one of Warwick Music’s bestselling publications. The band arrangement came about as a result of a stroke of inspiration. After teaching the piece to pupils the idea to arrange it for band was formed. The solo in the middle can be read, or if you have a budding player who likes to improvise feature them. The quavers throughout should not be swung! The

titre: When You Tell Me That You Love Me

description: From the mountains of the Appalachians to the shores of the seas, Americas history is reflected in its folksongs. Two of these song, Sweet Betsy From Pike and Frog Went A-courtin are presented here and provide young bands an excellent opportunity to work on contrasting styles, with a slow, expressive section followed by a happy, rollicking ending.
A quiet, contemporary setting of the beloved hymn, Amazing Grace, this work will be an expressive and musical highlight of any young band concert. (2 minutes 25 seconds)

Bachs last composition is an organ prelude based on the chorale Wenn Wie in Houchsten Noten Sin. Bukvichs re-composition includes this organ prelude plus the original melody and two of Bachs harmonizations, resulting in a highly emotional work. ( 5 minutes 30 seconds)
titre: Before Thy Throne I Now Appear

description: Based on the well-known British folk songs Lark in the Clear Air and Early One Morning, this selection opens with sensitive phrasing, dynamic nuances and contrasting tone colors. The second section is animated and playful. This piece is a real audience pleaser, as well as a valuable teaching tool. ( 1 minute 40 seconds)

This challenging, dramatic work appeared relatively early among the concert band projects of Walter Hartley. It is filled with Hartleys unique approach to mid-20th century serial composition at a vigorous allegro con brio. Bold unisons, expanded harmonic clusters, and soloistic passages appear in tandem with two recognizable themes that recur in a classic rondo form. This is a quick, smart, concise look at an

Each movement of this fine new composition presents a different color musically. A fresh, new, contemporary work with great musical integrity, this piece is going to be a welcome addition to the good literature for good bands.

A highly rhythmic contemporary work in the style of the traditional Italian Saltarella, this selection was first presented at the Midwest International Band and Orchestra Clinic in 1999 by the Owasso High School Band from Tulsa, Oklahoma, under the direction of their conductor and the composer, David Gorham. This pieces was an instant success and, with its driving rhythms and great energy, is sure to delight bands

A classic "Grande marcia" in the Italian style, The Florentiner is now available in an edition for modern concert bands. Conductors, musicians, scholars and audiences will enjoy this march in the first American edition that is faithful to the original Fucik manuscript.

This energetic, imaginative work presents the popular patriotic melody of America in an assortment of musical variations. Beginning with a brilliant, very American fanfare, the basic theme follows in a highly rhythmic, multi-metered setting, which leads to several other contrasting presentations, including a lyrical tuba solo and beautiful chorale settings, all which lead to a stirring finale. (6 minutes 30 seconds)

Sousa completed the full score of The Belle of Chicago on July 23, 1892, in Washington, D.C., one week before his discharge from the Marine Corps to form his own civilian band which, incidentally, was based in Chicago. (2 minutes 45 seconds)
Bukvich employs 17 different percussion instruments and the singing of all the wind instrumentalists in this epic composition named for the English victory in 1415 at Agincourt.

This beautiful chorale setting of "Jesus Loves Me" has become a young band classic and is a favorite in concert band programming. The soothing harmonies provided by this master band composer enhances the simple beauty of the melody and makes a very effective musical presentation for groups of all levels. Provide a peaceful and memorable moment to you performance with this very special selection.

Brilliant, dramatic original overture commissioned for the United States Air Force Band in 1991. Celebrating 25 years of publication, this repertoire standard appears on a number of state lists. A showpiece from a major American composer that is a consummate concert opener, final selection or encore for the mature band.
An excellent selection to develop contrasting styles of playing legato and marcato. Appealing melodic lines are sure to please.

Scored to be successfully performed by junior or senior high school bands with limited instrumentation. The composer has provided a work of colorful melodies and exciting rhythms specifically adapted for such bands. Youll find this to be especially effective for less experienced bands. (3 minutes)

This work opens with full rich bell-tones and full brass sonorities, which lead to a rhythmic, energetic unison theme. In the middle is a beautiful legato-rubato section featuring the woodwinds with flowing melodies and countermelodies. A big ending concludes this ideal piece for young band.

Opening with the traditional Red River Valley, this selection offers experiences in legato phrasing with dynamic nuances. The Mexican Clapping Song follows, reinforcing the understanding of 6/8 meter. Every wind instrument has the melody at some time.
This exciting new original work offers an opportunity to learn minor keys, different styles and contrasting time signatures, making it a great choice for concert or festival.

An exceptional work based upon the well-known hymntune. Both musical and sonorous, the composer extracts every ounce of power available in the spectacular conclusion. Adding to the finale is an optional organ part, making it especially effective a concert closer. This is one of several sacred settings available from the talented pen of Claude T. Smith. (5 minutes, 45 seconds)
titre: Canticle All Creatures Of Our God and King

description: A unique, quiet work in 3/4 time, which is legato and melodic, providing an excellent opportunity to introduce minor scales. (2 minutes 45 seconds)
A dynamic, dramatic selection that emphasizes the "dark" qualities of the key of F minor, while presenting and utilizing several contrasting styles.
From the creative pen of one of the most imaginative composers writing for band today, this work is a fitting sequel to the Bukvich legacy, which includes Voodoo and Symphony #1, In Memoriam Dresden.

The allegro sections use the articulated diatonic scale/arpeggio patterns in upper voices and the legato passages include important moving lines for 2nd and 3rd players. Contrasting sonorities in the lyrical andante provide excellent phrase teaching. ( 6 minutes 6 seconds)

Based on an origianl theme by Franz Hayd, this is a wonderful opportunity introduce young players and their audiences to this great composer. The attractive melody is played by every section at some time during the piece allowing everyone a musical experience in the spotlight. Concise learning objectives make this an educational as well as rewarding experience.

You are sure to please and delight everyone when you open your performance with this rhythmic and joyful selection. It sounds much more advanced that it actually is and is ideal for festival/contest performance situations. (5 minutes 12 seconds)

A programmatic original march for young players. A playable yet catchy bugling part can feature your young trumpet section but is also cued in other sections. The perfect opening number for getting audience attention and developing player confidence. ( 1 minute 45 seconds)

Singing melodies and strong rhythmic energy make this overture attractive for contest or concert use. The technical demands are limited and the scoring is always well-conceived. This composer is making his mark in the band community with good solid writing.

A major work for virtuoso soloist and virtuoso wind ensemble. This work by a master craftsman shows the musical integrity and compositional skills that have earned him a position in the first rank of American composers. One of the best works ever written for this combination, this concerto provides the serious conductor and the mature wind ensemble with a brilliant work for exciting results.
titre: Concerto #2 For Piano and Wind Ensemble

description: One of the great classic Sousa marches, this edition is based on research combining early editions and historically informed Sousa performances. Now bands and conductors can present this great traditional march with the style and interpretation that made Sousa famous.

This symphonic setting of classical American patriotic music will be a very useful teaching piece, while serving as a most effective program selection. America and America, the Beautiful are scored in lyrical settings along with exciting original fanfares and other American themes. (3 minutes)

This "Winter Holiday Celebration" presents four of the seasons most popular and enduring songs in an enjoyable, playable setting. The songs used include: Joy to the World; Hark! The Herald Angels Sing; Jingle Bells and We Wish You a Merry Christmas.

Beethoven wrote this work for a military band, and its popularity continues today. This scoring provides a unique opportunity for young band students and their audiences to experience an original work by one of the worlds greatest composers.

This work by a perennial favorite composer-arranger is an arrangement of two traditional Welsh folk songs. The lovely Ash Grove will give the students experience in expressive legato phrasing, and the Men of Harlech offers a contrasting marcato style. An outstanding choice for festival or concert.

This popular medley of marches by the "March King" has been a part of the repertoire of the U.S. Marine Band tour concerts for many years. Now available for the first time, bands everywhere can bring a touch of class and this great American musical tradition to their concerts and their audiences.

The Chautauqua and the two-step dance are early American institutions providing the background for this light work for the young band. One of the most famous Sousa marches -Washington Post- was a very popular two-step in America and Europe.

An exciting, playable work for festival or concert, with a fitting title. Jubiloso is in contrasting styles, with parts and rhythms offering a challenge to players, yet is within the abilities of better school bands.

One of the worlds most famous marches, Semper Fidelis is the official march of the United States Marine Corps. Finally, it is available in an edition prepared by the director of the U.S. Marine Band, as actually played by that great organization.

This favorite march by the German composer of military band music at the turn of the century is presented in a fresh new scoring of the original complete manuscript as performed by the United States Marine Band, arranged by its conductor.

A musical "Celebration of Canada," this exciting work combines thematic material from the Marseillaise and Rule Britannia, signifying Canadas national heritage. These are followed by a majestic chorus of O, Canada for a dramatic and fitting salute to this great country.

Another outstanding festival/concert selection, this exciting and highly playable work opens with strong rhythmic brass joined by contrasting woodwinds as the work develops. The cantabile section features melodic solos for flute and clarinet and later woodwind choir before combining with the brass for a beautiful slow section. This work concludes with a recapitulation and a driving rhythmic ending.

Taken from Puccinis first opera, this is the frenzied dance of the witches as they cast an evil spell on an unsuspecting victim. The fiery dance builds in speed and intensity providing a dazzling display of energy and excitement. While its absolutely faithful to the original orchestral work, it makes a wonderful transcription for the concert band repertoire.

Another fabulous arrangement from Adrian Taylor of popular tunes for Junior Wind Ensemble.  It is not necessary to have all parts being played for these arrangements. Most will work fine with just the two Trumpet/Clarinet parts and a bass line from trombones, tubas or bassoons. With the exception of the bassoon part, all instruments have a part 1 (more advanced and with key signatures) and a part 2 (easier music,
titre: Music for Junior Wind Band Vol. 3

description: From the mountains of the Appalachians to the shores of the seas, Americas history is reflected in its folksongs. Two of these song, Sweet Betsy From Pike and Frog Went A-courtin are presented here and provide young bands an excellent opportunity to work on contrasting styles, with a slow, expressive section followed by a happy, rollicking ending.

This highly original new work uses creative techniques to increase both the aural and the visual resources of the modern concert band, effectively creating an exciting new rhythmic musical adventure. The title alludes to the use of hand clapping as an integral part of the composition. The composer states, "I intended the use of the clapping to be an integral part of the fabric of the piece. It is not a novelty

A very playable, and very descriptive composition, this musical narrative tells the story of a hero and his adventure, musically leading us into a war with polytonality as the battleground. The upper winds introduce the main theme, which is then counterattacked by the lower winds. All this time the percussion plays a steady drone to the rhythm of the battle. The work ends with the hero emerging triumphantly in a

This is the best known of the many works written by E.V. "Honey Boy" Cupero during his successful career as a cornetist, band leader, music director, arranger, and composer. First published in 1914, it is a classic example of marches from this era, and it was very popular with American minstrels and circuses.
Contrasting playing styles - along with the Dorian Mode - make this fresh new work an outstanding addition to the young band library.

This beautiful chorale prelude, written as a musical memorial, opens with an antiphonal trumpet theme, which is followed by a tutti scoring leading to a modulation and development in the new key. The trumpet theme is reintroduced and the music builds to an impressive majestic finale using the entire band.

This melodic and lyrical work presents the perfect opportunity to emphasis legato articulation, shaping phrases and controlled dynamics. It provides a beautiful quiet and peaceful moment that will be welcome on any concert. (2 minutes 30 seconds)

Written to commemorate the 75th anniversary of the Richmond, Missouri High School Band, this will be a welcome work by those teachers who have come to enjoy the musical and educational value of Sewards compositions for school bands.

This imaginative, creative work will be great fun for the players and the audience alike. Contrasting styles and dynamics, combined with the introduction of modes and modality make this an interesting and unique work. Simple improvisation can be introduced in the Aeolian mode.

This work was commissioned by the University of Kansas to celebrate the Inauguration of the 16th chancellor, Dr. Robert Hemenway. It opens with bold fanfares that lead into a bright scherzo section, which is followed by a traditional processional. The entire work culminates with a return of the fanfares and a rousing, fast-paced finale.

Lafourche Parish (pronounced "LaFoosh") was commissioned by the East Thibodeaux Jr. High School Band. A stirring grade 3 work suitable for festival or contest performance, it is designed to provide young bands with an exciting, contemporary work that is very playable.

This intriguing new work conjures up images of chants from other eras, and perhaps even other civilizations. Using ostinato rhythms and lively percussion writing, Barrett has fashioned an eminently playable composition that is effective and moving.

This music is toe tappin, rollicking and energetic, combining the characteristics of the barnyard dance and the enthusiastic appeal of a chorus shouting "Hallelujah!" The piece is something of a rondo, and will be fun to play.

This programmatic work depicts a primitive rite in sound. Cast in three sections, the piece uses contemporary harmonies and colorful percussion to display the moods and energies of a long-ago ceremony. This is the first addition to this series by the prominent American composer Elliot Del Borgo, and adds a new dimension. (3 minutes)
This new arrangement provides a spectacular opportunity to feature a strong clarinet section with one of the most tuneful and enjoyable works from the orchestral repertoire.
A quiet, contemporary setting of the beloved hymn, Amazing Grace, this work will be an expressive and musical highlight of any young band concert. (2 minutes 25 seconds)

This beautiful chorale setting of "Jesus Loves Me" has become a young band classic and is a favorite in concert band programming. The soothing harmonies provided by this master band composer enhances the simple beauty of the melody and makes a very effective musical presentation for groups of all levels. Provide a peaceful and memorable moment to you performance with this very special selection.

A brilliant work written for the Strategic Air Command (SAC) Band, this selection is certain to quickly establish itself in the libraries and repertoire of mature bands who are looking for a fresh work which effectively exploits the sparkle and excitement of the wind ensemble or symphonic band. With synthesizer tape and optional choral parts, this work will be a major highlight on any program captivating band and

Babylon opens with a subtle percussion introduction followed by the statement of the motive by the flute, then resolving into the developmental section utilizing fragments of the motif. Again the percussion sets up a driving introduction to further the developmental section, this time in an allegro setting. Rich harmonies and active percussion lines prevail with this piece, making it one of this composers best works

Written for and dedicated to the University of Oklahoma Wind Symphony in honor of its inaugural concert in its new concert hall, this is a brilliant "fanfare/opener" that displays the creativity and compositional technique of this talented young composer.

This happy, festive musical celebration is a work that will delight players and audiences with its infectious spirit and energy. There is a sense of motion and movement that will brighten up any rehearsal or concert situation, and which celebrates the youthful energy and enthusiasm of young band students everywhere.

This very playable work is based on a traditional carol which was sung in the Sussex area of southern England. The beautiful melody is presented first in a simple statement of the original carol. It then undergoes a variety of different treatments and key centers which ultimately propel the work to a large, grandiose ending. This work is perfect for your holiday concert, or as a contrasting selection at festival.

A brief, accessible work by wind band standards, Sinfonia (1961) demonstrates some of the serial compositional techniques embraced by Walter Hartley at the midpoint of the 20th century. The piece is neoclassical in form and approach, yet still stretches the boundaries of tonality and melodic conventions - a common practice at the time of its creation. Performers will appreciate this newly engraved edition that was

From the creative pen of this talented young composer, we have Barretts latest contribution to the exciting contemporary literature for band. While not technically difficult, this work is extremely effective, as it presents four contrasting musical sections beginning with The Summoning, which opens with a very commanding tutti entrance that evolves into a quieter, mysterious section, then develops with a sense of
A majestic march in 4/4 meter that will be fun to play and interesting to program for the beginning band.
An exciting new overture by the popular composer of Continental Overture and Cambridge Park.
A great concert opener, tuneful, yet rhythmically exciting!

This new edition represents research combining early editions of the march and historically informed Sousa performance practices. The editor has examined first editions of the march, performance notes of former Sousa Band members, and performance markings in the Sousa Band encore books in the U.S. Marine Band library. Additionally he studied historic recordings of the march including those by the Sousa Band and by

This exciting new work is based on traditional Slavic melodies, and it captures the spirit and energy of the folk culture of this region. The work represents the spirited, robust people, who have frequently been oppressed; yet their defiance, patriotism, and nationalist culture can not be suppressed. This is a high energy work that contains widely contrasting musical sections reminiscent of the colorful folk dances

Another classic Sousa march edited by the noted Sousa and march authority Frank Byrne, this work is presented with all of the class and integrity for which the Frank Byrne Editions are known. They are based on meticulous research by one of the leading experts in this field. The Sousa Band enjoyed its longest single engagement from September 30, 1915, to June 4, 1916, in an extravaganza presented in the New York

Finally, a spectacular festive new work sure to be the musical highlight of the holiday season. Using familiar melodies associated with the holiday season, this brilliant new composition was written for the United Sates Air Force Band, Col. Lowell E. Graham, commander/conductor. An exciting selection that is a showcase for all sections of the band, it is sure to be a crowd pleaser.

Brilliant, dramatic original overture commissioned for the United States Air Force Band in 1991. Celebrating 25 years of publication, this repertoire standard appears on a number of state lists. A showpiece from a major American composer that is a consummate concert opener, final selection or encore for the mature band.

Singing melodies and strong rhythmic energy make this overture attractive for contest or concert use. The technical demands are limited and the scoring is always well-conceived. This composer is making his mark in the band community with good solid writing.

Based on a work by Telemann, this march setting provides the young musician with the opportunity to play with good "march style" while being introduced to an important period of our musical history. Dynamic contrast and style are important musical objectives.

This dramatic work is built upon a strong rhythmic motif. There is very good use of imitation throughout and an excellent recurring fugal section. A challenging, yet solidly doubled and scored composition, this piece displays exciting use of percussion as we have all come to expect from this gifted composer.

Based on tunes from William Walkers Southern Harmony (1835), this setting gives new life to those rousing American tunes that are so much a part of our musical heritage. Commissioned by the ACC Heritage of America Band.

The folkdance qualities of this piece will make it enjoyable for both players and audiences alike, and will give your young students the chance to experience some of Holsingers style at an easy level.

A fresh new concert march in the great American march tradition, this work combines contemporary rhythms, harmonies and scoring with the solid rhythmic march style that is such an important part of our concert band heritage.
This selection introduces young players to one of the most famous of all compositions.

Finally there is a setting of this most beautiful Scottish air that can be enjoyed by younger players. Capturing the essence of one of Scotlands most famous melodies, this work will provide young ensembles with the opportunity to demonstrate beautiful, lyrical, expressive playing. ( 3 minutes 15 seconds)

Combining modern "jazz-rock" rhythms with the standard, traditional 12-bar blues form results in a rhythmic jazz march that will be fun for bands and audiences alike. "Flexible" percussion parts enable everyone in the percussion section to play.

Designed for the school band with limited technical ability and/or instrumentation. The lively rhythmic melody is set to harmonic backgrounds that are easy for the player to relate to. Percussion parts are interesting and logical, as are parts for the 2nd and 3rd players of brass and woodwinds.

Every player needs to play the choromatic scale. Every player likes to play the blues. And everyone likes to have a good time! So here is a fun way to play the blues and play the chromatic scale at the same time. The players should learn while having fun, and should have fun as they learn; and both the players and the audience should have a really good time!

This new definitive edition of one of the "March Kings" greatest compositions is a welcome addition to the historic legacy of the modern concert band. Meticulously researched and studied, and based on the actual parts and materials used by the Sousa Band on their legendary tours, this is a tour de force that will be enjoyed by fine bands for many years.

Commissioned to commemorate its 20th anniversary season, this work was written for the Nebraska Wind Symphony, Omahas community band, in 1997. It is in traditional overture form, with a bold introductory theme in the horns answered by the trumpets. The material that follows presents the main theme in solo voices followed by the entire band. Contrasting material follows, leading to a recapitulation and eventually to a
Glenaire is a contrast of styles, dynamics, tone colors and articulations. It opens with a legato lyrical section followed by a spirited allegro.

Here is a work that is fun to play, perfect for festivals and concerts, and is an excellent teaching piece. The maestoso introduction leads into a march section, then a lyrical treatment of the main theme, and finishes with a dynamic finale.

A major work for virtuoso soloist and virtuoso wind ensemble. This work by a master craftsman shows the musical integrity and compositional skills that have earned him a position in the first rank of American composers. One of the best works ever written for this combination, this concerto provides the serious conductor and the mature wind ensemble with a brilliant work for exciting results.
titre: Concerto #2 For Piano and Wind Ensemble

description: Reflecting the great tradition of the British military bands, this work will be a popular addition to any young band concert.

A two-movement work dedicated to the legendary band director, Paul Enix, from Midwest City, Oklahoma, Gorhams new composition opens with a beautiful lyrical section that features the rich, full sonorities of the woodwind choir. The contrasting second movement is in the style of a gigue, with lilting, catchy rhythms. This very musical piece will be an excellent contest or festival selection.
A spirited march using rhythmic and melodic patterns that are fun to play and hear.

This musical portrait of a Spanish Christmas contains some of the most loved songs throughout the world, including: A La Nanita Nana; Oi Betlehem; Jubilosamente and Fum, Fum, Fum. This lovely sensitive medley of ancient carols is a welcome addition to any winter concert!

This ceremonial march was commissioned by the North Hills High School Band of Pittsburgh, PA. The work opens with the customary percussion and brass marcato, which leads into the theme played by the cornets. Interesting lyrical counter-melodies are written for the woodwinds with the entire band concluding the work in an exciting fanfare ending. An outstanding choice for processionals, pageants or contests.
This happy piece includes distinctive use of the woodwind and brass choirs. It includes contrasting styles, meters and tempos and a big ending.

This 1987 work is characteristic of the lyrical style capabilities of Claude T. Smith. Opening with a brilliant fanfare it moves into the lyrical section featuring woodwind solos, brass chorale and woodwind choir. Development is then toward a rollicking finale. A challenging work eminently playable by good high school and college/university bands.

Here is an exciting composition full of the multi-rhythms combined with the Smith harmonies that make his works unique. Following a jubilant introduction, the saxophones set the melodic line, which is augmented by the full band. Brass pyramids lead into a slow lyrical section with French Horn backgrounds. A modulation follows leading into a recap of the opening theme. The driving percussion pattern is soon augmented

This work opens with a dramatic adagio maestoso consisting of broad contrasting rhythms and dissonant brass harmonies. It then leads to the bright allegro con spirito that is marked with rhythmic chordal figures under flowing melodic lines and exciting meter changes. A brief andante expressivo supplies a change of mood and texture before the grandiose and powerful ending. A highlight for any program.

An exciting, energetic work with beautiful slow melodic sections, this piece was written specifically to be performed by school bands; however, the level of excitement and the musical interest will make it popular with bands at all levels. The brilliant fanfares, captivating rhythms and rich sonorities are the legacy of this outstanding composer.

This clever piece of writing is a compilation of some of Americas favorite girlfriends...girls such as Buffalo Gals; I Dream of Jeannie; Lil Liza Jane; Oh, Susanna and others celebrated via the magical pen of the incomparable Warren Barker. A true audience pleaser fit for any concert performance.

Irish Interludes offers students experience in slow, expressive phrasing with the hauntingly beautiful Bendemeers Stream, contrasted by the rollicking The Girl I Left Behind Me, which contains dynamic contrasts and uses all the common 16th-note patterns.

Based on the ballad In the Gloaming, this work begins by challenging students with sensitive phrasing and dynamic nuances, followed by a frisky barn dance that will delight students and audiences alike. (2 minutes 5 seconds)

Ryebuck Shearer is an Australian folk song full of rhythmic vitality. The song is about a sheep shearer who believes he is capable of shearing "a hundred and more" sheep daily. His song contains the carefree quality of a man who is no ones servant, and lives the hard but joyous life as one who works with his hands for his wages.

Ireland is the original home of many of our most loved and cherished songs and melodies. Several of these classic songs are included in this musical tour of Ireland. The work begins with the lovely and haunting ballad, O, Danny Boy. This is followed by a stirring rendition of The Wearing of the Green, which is in turn followed by a march style setting of Minstrel Boy.

A very playable, and very descriptive composition, this musical narrative tells the story of a hero and his adventure, musically leading us into a war with polytonality as the battleground. The upper winds introduce the main theme, which is then counterattacked by the lower winds. All this time the percussion plays a steady drone to the rhythm of the battle. The work ends with the hero emerging triumphantly in a

A brilliant work written for the Strategic Air Command (SAC) Band, this selection is certain to quickly establish itself in the libraries and repertoire of mature bands who are looking for a fresh work which effectively exploits the sparkle and excitement of the wind ensemble or symphonic band. With synthesizer tape and optional choral parts, this work will be a major highlight on any program captivating band and
This modal work in Rondo form will showcase any good young band at either festival or concert performances.

It is easy to imagine the quiet, beautiful river, with its great trees and lush vegetation, flowing downstream. This music depicts a fascinating journey, at times gaining momentum as the stream twists through the various bends, and increasing or decreasing in speed as the river channel gets deeper or shallower, or gets wider or narrower. A beautiful, romantic journey that eventually ends as serenely as it began.

The most famous and best known graduation, commencement, or ceremonial processional march in an effective, yet technically easy edition. Written within the technical abilities on any young band, yet full and mature in its musical presentation, this new setting will be welcomed by any band needing to play commencement without enough rehearsal time, or without their more mature graduating players.

This most effective setting of the famous Canon done especially for young players provides an opportunity to personally experience the magic of this wonderful tune that has delighted both players and audiences for over 300 years.

A major work commissioned by and for the U.S. Army Ground Forces Band, this selection displays the technical virtuosity of the modern concert band in a demonstration of colors and textures, which will excite the band and the audience alike. The piece concludes with a blazing finale, which will "bring the house down".
A refreshing, contemporary composition, which introduces the young band to mixed meter in an uncomplicated way. An excellent teaching piece!

A 16 bar introduction builds to a climax leading to the stirring main theme with unison trumpets. The slower middle movement features a lovely melody scored in a lush, tutti Barker style. A majestic restatement of the original theme culminates in a flashy ending. Sure to be a contest winner.
A descriptive, programmatic work, which has already been successful with players and audiences, this selection will be a popular addition to the young band repertoire.
An expressive setting of O'Twas on a Bright Mornin'.
This great march by the "March King" has been edited to provide conductors and musicians with the most authentic edition ever printed of this famous work as it was performed by the Sousa Band.

A delicate opening features the flutes stating the countermelody followed by the entire ensemble. A few various solo passages lead into the true theme My Shepherd Will Supply My Need. The powerful and chilling scoring of the marvelous old folk melody will have you reprogramming it year after year.
titre: Overture On An Early American Folk Hymn

description: Expect the unexpected in this fun and creative composition!

This spirited new work dedicated to the Strategic Air Command Band showcases the brass and percussion in brilliant opening and closing sections and contrasts this with a lyrical second movement featuring the woodwinds. On Wings is ideal for festival or concert and will appeal to both performer and audience alike.
titre: On The Wings Of The Chosen

description: From the composer of Continental Overture, this is another outstanding piece for young bands that is sure to become a standard contest/festival piece. Solid scoring combined with interesting rhythms and flowing melodies will make this work popular with directors, players and audiences.

This vibrant, rhythmic, melodic original march is in the style of a traditional rag, "two-step" dance or march tune from an earlier era. The work showcases the percussion section, and provides all an opportunity to participate in this happy musical experience.

Babylon opens with a subtle percussion introduction followed by the statement of the motive by the flute, then resolving into the developmental section utilizing fragments of the motif. Again the percussion sets up a driving introduction to further the developmental section, this time in an allegro setting. Rich harmonies and active percussion lines prevail with this piece, making it one of this composers best works

Based on a work by Telemann, this march setting provides the young musician with the opportunity to play with good "march style" while being introduced to an important period of our musical history. Dynamic contrast and style are important musical objectives.

Looking for an exciting, different but still traditional setting of a march ? Then you and your students will enjoy this original work composed in 1973 for a foreign tour band. Both woodwind and brass writing is playable for good junior high bands as well as high school groups. Ranges are moderate, rhythms tricky but within the grade level of the work. (2 minutes 30 seconds)

Best described as a contemporary chorale, this moving and introspective work demonstrates colors, textures and contrasts that are possible with the modern concert band. The independent and interweaving melodic lines make this a study in phrasing and interpretation for both conductor and performer. A work well suited as a contest warm-up selection. (4 minutes 10 seconds)
A spirited, tuneful original work with a touch of Americana that makes a fine choice for concert and contest appearances.

This emotional, contemporary work has gained widespread acceptance in recent years. Written in remembrance of the firebombing of the German city of Dresden, Bukvich combines the most traditional techniques with the most contemporary, including representational notation.

Youll find instant success with this fresh sounding, contemporary work. Combining contemporary concepts with musicality and active percussion this has proven to be one of Rolands best. (5 minutes, 10 seconds)

A most exciting and intriguing work for advanced bands from this gifted composer. Comissioned as well as premiered by the Arkansas All State Band, this work has established a place in programming repertoire for upper-level ensembles. (9 minutes)

Commissioned by the Richmond (MO) High School Symphonic Wind Band for their 75th Anniversary Concert, this work depicts a rollicking "Heart of America" celebration, which can be enjoyed by any good high school or college band.

Nancy Seward has combined two of the most beloved sea shanties. Shenandoah offers experience with dynamic nuances and legato style, with the phrases clearly marked. The Drunken Sailor, marked lively, reinforces all of the basic 16th note patterns for all instruments in a detached style, which includes a variety of articulation and dynamic contrast.

This wonderful march written by John Philip Sousa was originally published in 1918. Frank Byrne, Administrative Assistant to the Director of the Marine Band, has edited this march so it will provide an opportunity to perform it as Mr. Sousa would have done the work.
The winner of the first National Band Association/Merrill Jones Composition Award in 1992, this exceptional work is in a traditional, through-composed, dignified march style.

Commissioned by the 1979 Texas AA Honor Band, this composition continues to be a favorite of school bands around the world. From the dramatic opening statement by the trumpet and trombone to the allegro development section, you will find all the qualities one looks for in an excellent contest/festival selection. The mixed meter trademark of this composer is a prevalent feature throughout. (7 minutes)

Written during the Persian Gulf War by the distinguished composer of Sinfonia No. 4 and Chautauqua, this work is a personal musical statement in contrasting styles. This is the most programmatic of Hartleys wind ensemble "core repertoire" compositions.

A classic wind ensemble work in the core repertoire of all serious wind groups, this work has been recorded by many of the finest college and university bands and wind ensembles. It remains one of the important original wind works of the century. Wingert-Jones is pleased to be able to make this masterwork available to the discriminating conductor.

This dramatic work is built upon a strong rhythmic motif. There is very good use of imitation throughout and an excellent recurring fugal section. A challenging, yet solidly doubled and scored composition, this piece displays exciting use of percussion as we have all come to expect from this gifted composer.

A two-movement work dedicated to the legendary band director, Paul Enix, from Midwest City, Oklahoma, Gorhams new composition opens with a beautiful lyrical section that features the rich, full sonorities of the woodwind choir. The contrasting second movement is in the style of a gigue, with lilting, catchy rhythms. This very musical piece will be an excellent contest or festival selection.

This exciting, energetic original work for band by the talented staff arranger for the United States Air Force Band, Larry MacTaggart, was commissioned by the Omaha Westside High School Music Department. With excellent use of mixed meters and beautiful, soaring melodies, MacTaggart has created an artistic work that is effective musically and educationally, while serving as an enjoyable highlight for audiences and

Dedicated to a middle school/junior high honor band, this energetic and exciting selection makes extensive use of the percussion section as it develops into a middle section that exploits the colors of the various families of instruments. This well-crafted work is sure to be a successful addition to the school band repertoire.

This overture depicts the settlement of Cedar City, Utah, on November 11, 1851, by Mormon pioneers. Facing multiple hardships, these pioneers forged a new life in the harsh and cold mountain desert that surrounded them. Due to their determination, resourcefulness, and faith they laid the foundation for a thriving community.
titre: From The Cedars To The Mountain

description: This flag-waving symphonic celebration of our country is unabashedly patriotic! Beginning with a bold fanfare reflecting the strength and courage demonstrated by Americans, the piece continues a musical journey through several patriotic pieces, which include America, the Beautiful; Youre a Grand Old Flag and America (My Coutnry Tis of Thee).

This happy piece is an excellent teaching piece in addition to being perfect for a concert by a young band. The players get to demonstrate playing in contrasting styles, and with contrasting dynamics. Sunnypoint will provide a bright "sunny spot" on any concert at this level.

Song of Freedom is a stately, dignified patriotic work reflecting the patriotic fervor of the United States of America. The unity and sense of purpose demonstrated by Americans in the fall of 2001, and the determination to support freedom throughout the world, are reflected in this original composition.

This original trombone feature, a "smear" for trombones, was written in memory of C. Jack McCurley, a young, energetic, fun-loving trombone player who lost his life in an accident. He was a member of his middle school band in Jefferson City, Missouri, and his fellow students and teachers commissioned this work as a memorial to him. But they wanted a happy piece because he was a happy person.

An exciting, energetic work for young band, this selection provides great opportunities for contrasting styles, moods, and dynamics. It begins almost as a fanfare/march, and it evolves into very nice melodic sections that showcase the woodwinds.

A homage to the Lone Star State from one of the deans of 20th century band composition. Audiences everywhere will enjoy some of the most recognized melodies from a earlier time. And the musical styles are delightfully handled with mastery and class. Listen for The Yellow Rose of Texas; Red River Valley; San Antonio Rose; The Streets of Laredo and The Eyes of Texas.

A concert march in the finest tradition! Melodic, spirited, and expertly scored, this march is conceived in the mold of the classic English marches of the early 20th century. This is a nice change of pace for the "march" portion of your concert or adjudication.

This work introduces the imaginary kingdom of Lochria, a land of small, gentle folk, who avoid the outside world, but who love to laugh, help others, and enjoy their quaint life on the far side of the Ginger Mountains.
titre: In The Land Of The Lochrians

description: Take part in a musical journey through America that culminates in a thrilling finale on Battle Hymn Of the Republic. A perfect patriotic climax or finale for any concert or festival. (3 minutes)
Introduce the concept of modes and modality with this programmatic and educational work. Its both a valuable performing and enjoyable listening experience. (1 minute, 50 seconds)

An original march by the "March King," performed by the Sousa Band on tour and recorded by the United States Marine Band in 1976, but which was never published. Reconstructed from the original manuscripts from the Sousa estate and issued for the first time by Wingert-Jones.
A spirited march using rhythmic and melodic patterns that are fun to play and hear.
This modal work in Rondo form will showcase any good young band at either festival or concert performances.

Demonstrate how the beauty of nature can be represented through beautiful sounds with this musical representation. The majestic beauty of Canyonlands, Utah is showcased starting with daybreak, continuing during the day through the winding canyons and unique colors and culminating with a glorious sunset. An effective example of programmatic writing.

Make a powerful opening statement this concert season! Intense yet playable, youll appreciate the compositional creativity as well as the extensive yet not exotic percussion writing. Bands with limited instrumentation will benefit from the solid and effective scoring. A sure hit!
This stately processional march is reminiscent of the great coronation marches in band and orchestra repertoire. (2:25)

Celebre is a lively show piece that explores a fun and frolicking melody, is complimented by a beautiful ballad section that can really show off the ensembles musicality, and concludes with an uptempo, energetic finale.

This exciting excursion for winds and percussion is a flashy, fun display of technique and virtuosity, but it is not nearly as hard as it sounds. Written to be playable and accessible for most bands, it is a happy work that will be an entertaining and impressive addition to any concert (2 minutes 25 seconds)

Subtitled A Folk Song Set of Wisconsin, this attractive four-movement work is an exciting addition to the classic original suites for wind band. Written in the traditional style of the British band classics, this programmatic work will be a welcome addition to the repertoire of good bands. (11 minutes 45 seconds)

This Spanish celebration in music begins with percussion, which is joined by the low brass and low woodwinds, establishing a Latin mood. The melody voices enter with a simple melody, which begins to build, and continues building and developing until it leads to the finale of this happy celebration.

Focus on the Latin rhythms and musical concepts popular in Central and South America with the popular folk song, featuring the "Latin percussion of El Condor Pasa." Use all of your percussionists, and more. Students from other classes (history, geography, humanities, general music, choir, etc.) can be added to the percussion section playing Latin percussion instruments.

Few concert band works boast the swagger and panache of this exhilarating composition! A dramatic fanfare moves into a rollicking 6/8 journey, with the flavor of a Celtic jig. After a slower more expressive section, there is a short fughetta, followed by the melody stated with increasing intensity to a vibrant finish.

This one is a natural for that lighter moment in your young bands concert! The students and the audience will have fun with the hand claps and foot stomps. Theres lots of great teaching points too as your band gets to move through three simple keys!

This work is written in the Aeolian mode, and is meant to spur the imagination of young musicians who perform the music. It is a musical representation of an adventure by two Lochrian boys who have witnessed a shooting purple star passing in front of the moon. This leads to mysterious happenings and adventures.

Col. Bourgeois knowledge of performance practice in the original Sousa band is seen throughout this fine march. The regimental trumpets and drums should stand behind the band for the most authentic musical effect. It is truly gallant!
Composed by the talented band director/composer, this beautiful original ballad provides an excellent opportunity for developing musical expressiveness and lyrical, melodic playing.

This clever work brings exciting music and the spirit of Paris in a setting of the famous Can-Can which will enliven any band concert. Bright tempos, great style, and dynamic contrast combine with some clever rhythmic alterations in this entertaining program number.

It is easy to imagine the quiet, beautiful river, with its great trees and lush vegetation, flowing downstream. This music depicts a fascinating journey, at times gaining momentum as the stream twists through the various bends, and increasing or decreasing in speed as the river channel gets deeper or shallower, or gets wider or narrower. A beautiful, romantic journey that eventually ends as serenely as it began.
Thoughtful and introspective, this work provides a quiet, serene break from the hectic hustle and bustle of todays world. (4:00)

This piece opens with a dramatic fanfare which provides the basis for the principal thematic material for the piece. The aria that follows is reminiscent of a vocal aria in its purity and beauty. (6:05)
Written to commemorate the 150th birthday for the city of Lawrence, Kansas, this is a new march in a traditional style. (2:45)
This is the last composition from the pen of the talented composer and music educator, Nancy Seward. It is based on traditional English Christmas carols.

This attractive three-movement work is a reflection of some popular images from the state of Kentucky. The movements are titled: 1. In the Mountains, 2. Through the Mist, 3. Under the Moonshine. ( 7 minutes 14 seconds)

This exciting original overture for young band opens with a bold, majestic fanfare followed by a sudden increase in tempo and changes of texture. A quiet interlude and a return to the majestic fanfare leads to a stirring ending. (4:00)
An original composition by noted composer Barry Kopetz, this work provides a mature, musical format for presenting young musicians in concert. (3:15)

This composition is in the popular jazz-rock style and is based on the blues scale. It provides a rare opportunity for young players to experience the style of this type of music. (2 minutes 10 seconds)
A strong work for young band, this work will bring a touch of class to any concert. (2:00)
With traditional harmonies and a strong rhythmic pulse, this work will be a hit on any young band performance. (1:25)
Heres an original traditional march written by a legendary teacher. This tuneful march compares 2/4 and 6/8 meters and style, with emphasis on tonal and dynamic contrasts. (2:00)
Fire! is an intense and exciting concert piece that is quite accessible for intermediate bands. It employs a large percussion section offering interesting colors and rhythms.

Here is an extremely clever work for young bands from the creative mind of composer, Daniel Bukvich. It introduces the compositional technique of the tone row and the unusual title refers to the order of the notes used to create the initial motive for this educational and entertaining original work. (2 minutes 10 seconds)
Strauss wrote this stirring polka to celebrate the Austro-Hungarian Agreement of 1867, which stipulated self governance and representative governance for the Hungarians. (3:05)

From starting out on a journey and ultimately reaching the summit, this piece is a musical tribute to a fine high school music program, and to the teacher, Jim Oliver, of Lees Summit, Missouri, who led them there. (6:15)

Looking for an exciting, different but still traditional setting of a march ? Then you and your students will enjoy this original work composed in 1973 for a foreign tour band. Both woodwind and brass writing is playable for good junior high bands as well as high school groups. Ranges are moderate, rhythms tricky but within the grade level of the work. (2 minutes 30 seconds)

Upon leaving the Marine Band to form his own professional band Sousa wrote this classic original march. It has since become a standard in the repertoire of American concert bands and is now available in a new, historically accurate edition.

An absolutely delightful work that seems to explode off the page! From the opening Allegro Brilliante youll know this is a very special work. Striking and memorable with undeniable energy, this is concert band writing at its best. Sure to be a program favorite for years to come. Highly recommended!

Heres an absolutely delightful transcription from Schumanns popular Album for the Young. The music playfully describes Knecht Ruprecht, the dreaded legendary character that helped St. Nicholas deliver coal to the naughty children at Christmas. This is a well-crafted transcription that works extremely well for concert band.

The composer has successfully captured the musical essence and variety of four contrasting dance styles in this clever, imaginative work. Great musical contrast and interest highlight this exceptional composition which concludes with a driving, exciting display of brass and percussion.

Let the celebration begin! From the opening chords and ringing of chimes you know this is a work with special meaning. Written as a tribute to a fellow music educator, audiences and performers alike will recognize the respect, admiration and joy associated with this special person.
titre: East Of The Sun (and West Of The Moon)

description: The title says it all! Experience the vitality and energy that bubble throughout this concert overture. A work that captures the essence of each new spring, the abundance of new life and the annual rebirth of nature. Certain to lift everyones spirits.

This seasonal showcase features Good King Wencelas; God Rest Ye Merry Gentlemen; The Coventry Carol; Greensleeves; and Angels We Have Heard on High, presented in regal settings that accent their noble qualities.

Truly robust music to add fire to your program. Wickedly delightful phrases seem to spin out of control throughout this frenzied dance. Theres a brief respite to catch your breath before returning to the dance to finish. Clever and intriguing, it demands attention.

Soaring melodies, beautiful scoring, and musical excitement are all present in this new original work by the gifted arranger for the United States Air Force Band in Washington, D.C. Here is musical excellence at a grade level that can be enjoyed by bands everywhere. ( 6 minutes 45 seconds).

Based on the Shaker hymn Love (More Love), this is a lovely musical tribute to an outstanding teacher upon his retirement. It is a musical expression of great respect for his service to his profession, his students, and his school. This legacy will be carried forward through the many students whose lives he touched through music educaton.

An interesting combination of 3/4 time in the style of a march. This is the third work in a series of young band selections beginning with First Time Out followed by Second Time Around. Each work includes clearly stated learning and rehearsal objectives as well as program notes.
This march for young band is an energetic, exciting treatment of the famous "Goin Home" theme from Dvoraks New World Symphony, and should be enjoyed by both the players and the audience.

Based on a traditional German Christmas folk song popular in Europe. This charming melody makes an effective vehicle for introducing various 3/4 rhythms to young players and mallet instruments to young percussionists. Delightful as well as educational.

Effective, sensitive scoring brings out the various colors and beauty possible with concert band instrumentation. A quiet work that provides contemplation and reflection in the midst of todays complex and busy world. This will introduce how music can influence the spirit and emotions of the listener.

A major programmatic addition to young band repertoire describing the Niobrara River region. Subtitled sections include: Tubing on the River; Sunset in Cherry County; and Hoedown in Niobrara. We are fortunate to have the talented arranger of the United States Air Force Band contribute this attractive selection to developing band repertoire.

This exciting, energetic original work for band by the talented staff arranger for the United States Air Force Band, Larry MacTaggart, was commissioned by the Omaha Westside High School Music Department. With excellent use of mixed meters and beautiful, soaring melodies, MacTaggart has created an artistic work that is effective musically and educationally, while serving as an enjoyable highlight for audiences and

Dedicated and premiered at the Missouri Music Educators 50th Anniversary. This work opens with a strong statement based on thematic material, introducing a brisk allegro section which is followed by a slow lyric passage featuring the flute section. The allegro then resumes before a powerful and majestic conclusion. (5 minutes 30 seconds)

Another effective composition from this master teacher, Norwegian Vignettes contrasts the majestic marcato style of the opening with the light staccato of the B section. It also offers contrast in dynamic levels and tone colors, along with a study of the dotted 8th/16th pattern. This programmatic selection will enhance any concert setting.

An original dance selection written for the purpose of developing fluency in playing half-steps, this piece captures the flavor of the type of dance one might hear at a party on the beach in Latin American countries. The music is light and buoyant, with a strong Latin influence.

Written to commemorate the 10th anniversary of the Arkansas Winds Community Concert Band, Wilson Park opens with a high-energy introduction, starting with a brass fanfare followed by rapidly moving woodwinds that get this composition off to an exciting beginning. A tuneful, melodic work full of musical contrast.

Second Time Around is a stirring, melodic 4/4 (or common time) march for young bands in which everyone except the percussion has the melody at one time or another. This work provides young players with the opportunity to perform a march which is not technically difficult, but is very satisfying.

Noted Sousa researcher, Frank Byrne brings us a definitive edition complete with full score of this classic march. Composed at the request of the 1920 graduating class of the U.S. Naval Academy in Annapolis, its dedicated to Tecumseh, the famous Indian statue located at the Naval Academy. (2 minutes, 50 seconds)

This work was commissioned by the Altus, Oklahoma band program in memory of Angelique Mitchell. It begins with a plaintive, wistful melody in the clarinets and alto saxophones, who are joined later by the cornets and trumpets.

This piece is written in the great American march tradition that has been such a popular part of band concerts for more than 100 years. It is melodic, tuneful and provides an excellent opportunity for young performers to play a "traditional American march."

This work introduces the major themes from three of the most famous and popular symphonies ever written - Beethovens Symphony No. 5, Symphony No. 7 and Symphony No. 9 - which are readily recognizable and easily learned, serving as a good introduction to some of the great masterpieces of western civilization. (2 minutes 45 seconds)

This attractive work is full of rhythmic variety, as well as changes of orchestration and instrumentation. The catchy march melody is introduced by the clarinets and cornets, after which it goes through a series of creative transformations (or variations) in which the same musical ideas are presented in a variety of different musical formats and styles.

This thoroughly researched edition represents a study of first edition printings, performance notes of former Sousa Band members and markings in the Sousa Band encore books in the U.S.Marine library. All of these valuable resources have contributed to make this edition a historically accurate recreation. (2 minutes 41 seconds)

During World War One Sousa was asked to compose an American wedding march, and he fulfilled this request with this processional march. Subtitled Wedding March, Sousa dedicated the work to the American people. Stately and dignified, it is an excellent choice for academic processions or formal, ceremonial occasions.
Now a standard in the band repertoire, Bukvichs intriguing, creative work features many non-traditional performance techniques.

Heres a vibrant contemporary composition that offers a variety of styles, tempi and colors and it is still within the capabilities of young players. An excellent performance piece in the Achievement Series that will both educate students and impress audiences. (2 minutes 10 seconds)
An exciting, fun, novelty piece with a spooky flair, this piece is perfect for the first concert of the year. It is a concert rondo that gives each section a shot at the melody.

Demonstrate how the beauty of nature can be represented through beautiful sounds with this musical representation. The majestic beauty of Canyonlands, Utah is showcased starting with daybreak, continuing during the day through the winding canyons and unique colors and culminating with a glorious sunset. An effective example of programmatic writing.
Thoughtful and introspective, this work provides a quiet, serene break from the hectic hustle and bustle of todays world. (4:00)

This 2005 National Band Association composition award winner was inspired by the American minimalist composer Philip Glass. Shards of Glass comprises a repetitive series of chord changes. Each repetition enters with varied orchestration and introduces new contrapuntal lines and rhythmic figures. This is the type of literature mature ensembles enjoy performing.

This invigorating work is well worth your consideration. White River Revival takes you on a musical journey along the twists and turns of the White River, which stretches almost 700 miles through the beautiful Missouri and Arkansas countryside. Musical adventures relay the fun of trout fishing and an old-time religious revival held along the river. This is truly an audience-pleasing travelogue.
A regal fanfare opens this majestic new work. Interesting melodic development follows, including opportunities for soloistic playing, culminating in an exciting finale.

This simple, expressive setting was written for a performance at the World War II Veterans Memorial in Washington, D.C. It is symbolic of a generation of Americans who defended their country with honor and passion, expecting nothing in return. Very moving.
Whistle Tune is a melodic and rhythmic composition that is fun for students and audiences alike.

One of the most loved Christmas songs, I Heard the Bells on Christmas Day is presented in a new setting which intersperses snippets of Jingle Bells and Joy to the World. The audience will want to sing along with this great seasonal classic.

The French emperor, Napoleon Bonaparte, was one of the most colorful and successful European leaders of his era until his final battle at Waterloo. Napoleons forced surrender is the theme that inspired this new work for band.
An original work written in the style of Elgars famous Pomp and Circumstance, this work provides young bands with a ceremonial march in the grand tradition.

This happy, spirited work reflects the traditions of the Cumberland Mountains region in the Southeastern United States. The melody is passed throughout the ensemble, and the percussion section is put in the spotlight in this fun, exciting selection.

According to Greek legend, the spectacular view from Mount Olympus enabled the gods to see everything from their high vantage point. The splendor and grandeur of the scenery is breathtaking, and is aptly captured in this new work for concert band.

Reflecting the grandeur of the Ozark Mountains, this work is named for the Missouri county. The rolling melodies are broken by periodic outcroppings of jagged syncopation, painting both the forest-covered hills and the rocks and waterfalls that typify the Branson area.
The pageantry and ceremony of the Olympic Games are brought to the fore in this bold work. The excitement of this event makes for an upbeat moment in your concert program.

This work gives you a terrific opportunity to build musicianship in your band. The flowing eighth-note lines form a natural teaching moment to have your students listen across the band for tempo and balance. The music cascades downward creating images of beauty.

Inspired by a visit to Scotland, this musical journey is designed to invoke visions of the rugged beauty found throughout the northern reaches of the United Kingdom. This is a wonderfully descriptive work.

This piece opens with a dramatic fanfare which provides the basis for the principal thematic material for the piece. The aria that follows is reminiscent of a vocal aria in its purity and beauty. (6:05)

Upon leaving the Marine Band to form his own professional band Sousa wrote this classic original march. It has since become a standard in the repertoire of American concert bands and is now available in a new, historically accurate edition.

Experience the exploits of the great Spartan warriors through this bold musical portrayal. Beginning with a call to battle, the music builds as the proud army grows and drama builds. A final triumphant celebration of victory highlights the powerful conclusion. Young players will enjoy performing and audiences wont forget Warriors of Sparta.

Go on a nautical adventure with this brilliant musical depiction of one of natures greatest treasures! Based on the composers experience, this remarkable work conveys all the excitement and exhilaration of seeing a great Humpback whale leap from the sea. The unforgettable feelings captured in this concert work are nothing short of spectacular!

Finally! Now young bands can experience the excitement and drama of one of the most popular overtures from classical literature. The widely recognized themes have been well written for young players while still retaining the brilliance of the original. A must for every young band. Cannons are optional!

Fire up everyones imagination with this creative and unique selection. The special effects are easy and effective and will have audiences visualizing spaceships and strange wonderful creatures when this is performed. In fact, everyone will want to "phone home" after having a close encounter with this clever and effective piece for young bands.

This easy to play medley features The Holly and the Ivy; Hark! The Herald Angels Sing and We Wish You A Merry Christmas in a very attractive holiday package for young bands. The generous doubling of instruments will make this easy to prepare while a merry quote of Jingle Bells adds the finishing touch to this delightful finale for your Christmas concert!

These dances display Tchaikovskys remarkable grasp of symphonic writing and are among the very best of his dance sequences. Carefully transcribed for band, they are taken from the opera "The Oprichnik." The Oprichnik were the personal bodyguards of Tsar Ivan the Terrible. The opening dance features various woodwind solo passages that display a hauntingly poignant Slavic flavor. The second dance begins vigorously and

This wonderful transcription comes from the only comic opera written by Tchaikovsky, "The Slippers." Opening with a short, stately fanfare before bursting into a flurry of rhythmic activity, the music depicts energetic Ukrainian dancers. A true programming jewel for accomplished bands. Colorful and lively!

An outstanding example of suburb concert band literature! The majestic and noble opening leads the way to the main body of the work where the full expanse of the creative writing is displayed. The melodic lines are highlighted with occasional mixed meters as well as creative percussion writing. All these elements combine to make a first-rate concert selection that is accessible to a wide range of bands.

As exhilarating as a brisk race across a frozen lake, this selection will brighten the spirits and turn up the excitement this holiday season! Imagine ice skating around a lake where winter festivals are taking place. In one community youll hear Jingle Bells, in another youll hear folk music and in yet another youll hear Deck the Halls. Finally, as you race to the center of the lake youll hear the music of all three

Always a patriot, Sousa composed what may be his most programmatic march to honor World War I shipbuilders. Many sounds typical of early 20th century shipbuilding are featured including the sound of sirens, hammering, anvils and riveting machines. A delightful and stylish march with some very unique features!

Uplifting and inspiring, this work pays tribute to the promise and possibilities of tomorrow. In one aspect the title refers to the expansive horizon of the physical world; on a more personal level, it alludes to the wide horizon we see as the promise of our future. An opening fanfare is developed through driving rhythmic figures, which is finally fulfilled in the works broad, uplifting conclusion.

Striking in scope and distinctive in effect, this impressive work reflects the rich history and landscapes of a remarkable community. From the magnificent opening chords through the reflective contrasting sections, all represent important area landmarks. The ending provides the ultimate "snapshot" whereby the listener can envision the entire landscape in one glorious, panoramic view. A marvelous work!

Heres the perfect opening number for maximum attention and effect! Beginning with great energy and rapid tempos, through compelling rhythms and driving accents, this selection seems to virtually electrify the air. Limited ranges allow players to focus on the relentless rhythmic feel that is the essence of the piece. The marvelous percussion parts keep players totally involved and the level of intensity high

We all have had teachers profoundly influence and affect our lives. This work pays tribute to these dedicated educators. A quest for knowledge, a passion for learning, and a legacy of dreams...these are the gifts bestowed upon us by our best teachers. The expressive, meditative mood of this work provides an appropriate setting for us to reflect on how these gifts have enriched our lives. A most fitting tribute.

An absolutely delightful work that seems to explode off the page! From the opening Allegro Brilliante youll know this is a very special work. Striking and memorable with undeniable energy, this is concert band writing at its best. Sure to be a program favorite for years to come. Highly recommended!

Dedicated and premiered at the Missouri Music Educators 50th Anniversary. This work opens with a strong statement based on thematic material, introducing a brisk allegro section which is followed by a slow lyric passage featuring the flute section. The allegro then resumes before a powerful and majestic conclusion. (5 minutes 30 seconds)

The carnival is back in town! From the writer that brought us The Fortune Tellers Daughter, here is a return to all the atmosphere and allure of exotic sights, thrilling rides and amazing games of skill. All you need to do is step right up and get your ticket for delightful programming for young bands!

This beautiful Irish folktune is sometimes called the national ballad of Ireland and is one of the best-known and beloved ballads of all time. Carefully written for young band, this charming setting reflects all the beauty and appeal of this beloved song in a setting bands at all levels will enjoy performing.

This delightful piece for young bands provides an opportunity for young players to play in the ragtime style and introduces them to the world of jazz. Heres a great way to teach an important historic American musical style in an entertaining piece that will be fun for bands young and old!

The fabulous city described in literature, on stage and in film is now represented in a musical vision of stunning beauty and unusual grandeur. This wonderful setting for young bands evokes marvelous images while providing a majestic air to young band performances. Complete with learning objectives in all parts, directors will find this to be both educational and entertaining!

Blast-Off with the perfect opener to energize any elementary concert! Flashy brass melodies with nice woodwind countermelodies (all using just five notes) and driving rhythmic patterns in the percussion provide an "out-of-this-world" experience. It can be performed with as few as five percussionists; however, there are optional parts that will keep all your young space raiders completely involved in the mission!

First-year players will love performing this bold and heroic work at their first concert. Using the first few notes in most beginning band methods, this will be easy to prepare and a pleasure to perform. Make no mistake, this is not your average beginning band piece. Active percussion parts complement the winds parts which use simple quarter-note rhythms with full, dramatic effect! Very powerful!

Elementary and mid-level bands will enjoy performing this cute yet hip treatment of the seasons jolliest music. The addition of special percussion parts for your budding young percussionists will help them grow as musicians while adding a special touch to your holiday program. An entertaining addition to any holiday concert, well within reach of beginning players.

Bring a bit of nature to your performances with this delightful musical depiction young players will love. The chase is on as wood blocks depict frogs hopping away from musicians determined to capture their slimy prey. Carefully written for beginning players, it is a fun, descriptive work complete with a musical "yuck!" and a final "splash" of escape into the pond.

On April 19, 1995 the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma City was the target of a devastating bombing that resulted in a terrible lose of life, including 19 children to whom this work is dedicated. Re-creating the eerie atmosphere that lead up to this horrible event, it closes with a moving musical memorial for all the victims, offering a message of hope and comfort to all those involved. A truly

Delightfully imaginative, your students will visualize these cute little creatures climbing and scampering throughout this descriptive work for beginning bands. Fun to play as well as instructive, this is one piece that will entertain young musicians. The perfect selection for that first concert experience!

Whats that on the roof? You wont have trouble hearing the sound of hooves as your beginners have fun jammin on this fresh, fun arrangement of Up on the Housetop. Perfect for that very first winter concert, the simple rhythms and limited ranges make learning quick and easy. A few extra percussion instruments add to the fun and seasonal atmosphere.

Build confidence and enthusiasm in your beginners with this bold yet easy work. Preparing this brave and heroic work is easy as limited ranges and simple rhythms require minimal rehearsal time. Your young drummers will especially enjoy the exciting percussion parts that add to the power and pride of the piece.

The awesome power of an erupting volcano is displayed when you perform this beginning band work. Starting with the anticipation of an impending eruption, you can sense the level of danger increasing as the music builds. Then comes the climax as the inevitable eruption brings the piece to a final explosive finale!

Another effective composition from this master teacher, Norwegian Vignettes contrasts the majestic marcato style of the opening with the light staccato of the B section. It also offers contrast in dynamic levels and tone colors, along with a study of the dotted 8th/16th pattern. This programmatic selection will enhance any concert setting.

Fans of great, stately European marches will be drawn to this modern edition of this stylish march. Reminiscent of other popular marches by this composer, it incorporates the use of distinctive regimental trumpeting fanfares in the final strain. This modern edition allows todays wind bands to experience this wonderful march and display the true depth and effect of its grand style.

Johan Halvorsens In Memoriam, Opus 30 was written for the great Norwegian poet Bjornstjerne Bjornson. The two men became very close friends and Halvorsen composed a funeral march in Bjornsons honor upon his death in 1910. The musics link with Bjornson is underscored by the fact that it opens with a paraphrase of the Norwegian national anthem. At the peak, it suddenly falls away, and following a roll of the timpani,

While not well known, some of Tchaikovskys best symphonic writing is found in his operas and ballets. This selection from his only comic-fantasy opera actually featured a large on-stage wind band performing this polonaise! A well-crafted edition brings this wonderful work to life and provides an outstanding work for accomplished bands.

Close your eyes and become immersed in the soothing, carefree days of summer! Youll imagine a peaceful morning sunrise, the midday heat, a gentle rainstorm, and the clear blue skies that precede a magnificent sunset. Warm resonant sounds of woodwind and brass choirs with subdued percussion create a colorful evocative portrait that displays the full range of concert band sonorities. A fascinating work that will

A stunning work of regal scope and profound energy! Dedicated to all those who perform acts of service and kindness, it serves as a fitting tribute to those selfless individuals. A crown jewel in the realm of concert band repertoire!

Definitely written with a Celtic flair, this wonderful original work provides all the elements a band is looking for in a performance piece. The beautifully flowing opening lines feature melodic elements that enhance and display the ensembles musicality.
